Alabama: Northern —Returns from Lauderdale and Limestone counties.

Indiana: 2nd —No returns from Craw­ ford and Scott counties.

North Carolina: 13th —No returns from Surry County.

South Carolina: 2nd —Returns from the parishes of Prince William, St. Andrew's and St. Helena. 3rd—Returns from George­ town and Horry districts and All Saint's Parish. The Charleston Southern Patriot reported that Mitchell had been elected by a majority of 75. 4th—No returns from Lex­ ington and part of Orangeburgh. 7th—No returns from Union district. 86—Returns only from Clarendon district.

Tennessee: 8th—No returns from Stewart County.

Virginia: 3rd —Returns only from Chesterfield County. 5th—No returns from Buckingham County. 4th—Returns only from Brunswick County. 6th—No returns from Campbell County. 8th—No returns from Accomack and James City counties and the city of Williamsburg. 9th—No returns from Charles City, New Kent coun­ ties and the city of Richmond. 10th— Returns from Fluvanna and Nelson counties. 12th—Returns from King & Queen County. 13th—No returns from King George and Northumberland coun­ ties. 14th—No returns from Fairfax County. The Alexandria Gazette of April 18, 1827, reported that Mercer carried the county by 44 votes. 19th—No returns from Bath and Pocahontas counties. 20th—Returns from Botetourt and Rockbridge counties.

Special Elections. Mississippi: No returns from Adams, Claiborne, Greene, Hancock, Jackson, Jones, Madison, Perry, Pike, Warren and Washington counties. Ohio: 6th—Returns not identified were probably from Ross County. The Chillicothe Times, December 12, 1828, stated that Muhlenberg was elected by a small major­ity over Wallace.

Party representation in the House of Representatives as of the opening of the 21st congress on December 7, 1829 (reflecting special elections held prior to that date) was as follows: Jacksonians 132, Administration 72, Anti-Masons 5, Independents 1. There were two vacancies, in Pennsylvania's 16th District and Virginia's 10th. Maine's election process was still under way.

Incomplete Returns

I ndiana: 2nd -No returns from Jackson and Scott counties.

Kentucky: 9th -No returns from Bullitt County. The Advertister, August 22, 1829, reported that Wickliffe was elected by a majority of 660.

Mississippi: No returns from Clarke and Jackson counties. The Niles Register, September 27,1828, p. 67, gave the following returns: Hinds 4,566, Dickson 2,496, Bingaman 1,930 and Hail 1,407, adding "We know not whether they are complete."

North Carolina: 13th-No returns from Ashe County.

Ohio: 4th -No returns from Hancock and Wood counties. 7th -No returns from Lawrence County. The Athens Mirror, November 15, 1828, reported that Vinton had carried the county by 75 votes. 8th-No returns from Crawford, Knox and Licking counties. In Licking Stanbery had a majority of 776, according to the (Washington) U.S. Intelligencier, Octo­ ber 28, 1828. 14th-No returns from Sandusky County.
